 Ek simple rule yaad rakho: Recursion call ke andar jo kuch bhi hota hai, woh us call ke khatam hote hi mitti mein mil jata hai (gayab ho jata hai).
Aaiye isko line-by-line breakdown karte hain ki loop mein target wapas kaise same rehta hai:C++
for (int i = index; i < candidates.size(); i++) {
    temp.push_back(candidates[i]);
    
    solve(i, target - candidates[i]); // <--- CALL 1 (Maan lo i=0, yani Perk)
    
    temp.pop_back(); // <--- Backtrack (Yahan wapas aaye)
}
1. target - candidates[i] karne se asal target kam nahi hota!Jab aap likhte ho solve(i, target - candidates[i]), toh aap apne current function ke target variable ki value ko badal nahi rahe ho. Aap bas uski ek ghati hui value calculate karke agli call ko gift de rahe ho.Agar aapka original target = 10 tha, aur candidates[i] = 3 hai.Toh agli call (CALL 1) ke paas naya target jayega 7.Lekin jo aapki current function call hai, uske dimaag mein target abhi bhi 10 hi save hai! Uska apna target kharab nahi hua.2. Pop_back ke baad kya hota hai? (The "Reject" Moment)Jab CALL 1 (Perk waali branch) apna poora kaam khatam karke wapas aati hai, toh code agli line par jata hai: temp.pop_back();. Aapne Perk ko nikal diya.Ab loop ka agla turn chala: i badh kar 1 ho gaya (Munch).Ab dhyan se socho, jab loop i = 1 ke liye chal raha hai:Aapka temp wapas khali ho chuka hai.Aapka target abhi bhi 10 hi hai (kyunki current function ka target toh kabhi badla hi nahi tha!).Ab code chalega: temp.push_back(candidates[1]) (Munch ko pick kiya).Aur agli call jayega: solve(1, target - candidates[1]) $\rightarrow$ yaani 10 - Munch ke paise.
